@kbaley i am having the same problem have you been able to find a solution ?

EDIT: definitively problems arise when you start using builder.HasData(); This is definitively a bug.
I am using all the latest versions of .net and ef 7.0. If you need another example, I can upload mine  @maumar @ajcvickers

I'm having the same issue trying to seed with `.HasData()`.

```{ .c-sharp }
public void Configure(EntityTypeBuilder<MyDataModel> builder)
    {
        builder.OwnsMany(e => e.MyListPoco, ownedNavigationBuilder =>
        {
            ownedNavigationBuilder.ToJson();
        });
    }
```

The table is created as you'd expect with a field called MyListPoco of type nvarchar(max). I've tried the following:

``` { .c-sharp }
// On MyDataModel as an object.
builder.HasData( new { Key = 1, MyListPoco = new List<Foo> { new() { bar = 1, baz = "test" }});

// On MyDataModel as a string
builder.HasData( new { Key = 1, MyListPoco = "{\"bar\": 1, \"baz\": \"test\"}" });

// In a config of its own
builder.HasData( new { bar = 1, baz = "test",  MyDataModelKey = 1 });
```

Just for fun, I also tried adding Foo as a DbSet but no luck anywhere.
